		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message31220305">Personally I always prefer them because they add more information (or rather, they <em>lose less information</em>) from Japanese to English. It's not a perfect process, but getting as close as possible and with a simple learning curve is criticalâ€”not even to mention how cringeworthy some of Commie's tls from an honorific to some dated English slang can be.I also think all anime-goers, casual or not, should be aware of honorifics, in the same way one can't really enjoy most anime without understanding the basic facets of the culture and/or jokes and/or cliches.<br />
<br />
If I were the leader of a fansub group, however, I'd go localized. It simply attracts the most audience and on the point of bettering one's group, targeting the mainstream is rarely the wrong move.</div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig"><div style="text-align: center;"><!--link--><a href="http://myanimelist.net/clubs.php?cid=40791">QD</a><!--center--></div></div></td>
