		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message31223507">For me it's actually less about audience (viewers) and more about the fiction, that is, the setting and the characters.  In general, I don't think that non-Japanese people speaking non-Japanese languages should use Japanese honorifics, while I have less of a problem with honorifics being left intact for cases where it fictionally makes sense.<br />
<br />
In the fiction of the Baccano universe, the characters never speak Japanese--they're American (most native born with a handful of European immigrants) living in America, and they're speaking American English.  One could say that in the TV broadcast of the show, the voices are essentially "dubbed" into Japanese for the benefit of Japanese viewers, and because of that Japanese audience, honorifics are present in the dialog.  However, leaving the honorifics present in localization would (in my view) be putting the cart before the horse.  (In fact, I don't think that honorifics should have any place in the script for a show for Baccano, even in the Japanese script for Japanese viewers.)  Perhaps even worse is when these honorifics make their way into the English dub script; I believe Cowboy Bebop was guilty of this.<br />
<br />
On the other hand, Japanese people living in Japan and speaking in Japanese do use honorifics, and it seems appropriate for works to reflect that, especially in situations where choice of honorific can be significant.  As nil notes, leaving honorifics intact removes less information.  (That said,  I do feel that there is a tendency for localizations to fall back on Japanese honorifics when suitable replacements can be found--though this isn't always feasible due to things like script timing and such.)<br />
<br />
To call upon an example: in Full Metal Panic: Fumoffu (which has a Japanese high school as its setting), Kaname addresses another student as "senpai."  However, in the (official) English localization, this is translated as "senior."  While this is "technically" a correct transliteration and the word "senior" may be a more appropriate for a broader western audience, "senpai" carries implied meaning that "senior" does not.  In fact, watching FMF:F as a less mature anime viewer, one of the things that struck me about Kaname's wording is that it seemed incongruous with her behavior--she seemed affectionate toward him, yet addressing him as "senior" seemed very stiff and formal.  Even had I lacked the vocabulary to understand the meaning of "senpai," I would have rather been presented with a foreign word and be left to speculate its meaning based on context--I already had a good idea, and the transliteration actually drove me further away from the intended meaning rather than closer.<br />
<br />
You can have examples of both  present in the same work.  For example, Planetes is a science fiction story about a crew in space hailing from a variety of national backgrounds.  Two of the main characters are Japanese sharing company with a Russian and an American, and in the official English anime localization, the Japanese characters address each other as "kohai" and "senpai," and rightfully so--these describe their relationship (in early episodes, it's a mentoring relationship of sorts) and it's reasonable to assume that two Japanese people speaking to each other would address each other so.  However, the junior Japanese crew member quite appropriately only uses "senpai" when addressing her Japanese senior--all of the other crew members are simply addressed by name, as one would expect.  (One would presume that from an in-universe fiction perspective, the two Japanese crew members speak to each other in Japanese, while the rest of the dialog is in English.)</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
