		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message31228629">I agree a lot with Kupier. Whether or not honorifics should be kept is really dependent on the setting of the story. It also has to do, though, with how important the honorific itself is to understanding the relationships of the characters and such, though, and that is also true for really any term used in the original language that doesn't have an exact translation (in both meaning and implications). If it is possible to portray the original intent (or very close) in the language that the work is being translated into, then that should be the work used, because a good translation should strike a balance between portraying the intent of the work and sounding/reading as natural as possible in the new language. Honorifics and other things not in the language may help get the meaning across but they also get in the way of immersion and flow, especially when the viewer isn't accustomed to those terms or it is a particularly less common term that would require something like a translation note (something I really hate unless it is absolutely necessary).</div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig">&quot;My tables-meet it is I set it down<br />
That one may smile, and smile, and be a villain.&quot;</div></td>
