		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message31340169">I remember when first starting to watch anime, I was insanely confused about why there had to be weird letters at the end of every name. Eventually, with the help of some Google search, and quite a lot of figuring out on my own, I began to understand. If you asked me when I first started to understand honorifics, I would definitely say they don't belong in a subbed anime_ after all, the point is to make viewers who read English understand the meaning of the anime. <br />
<br />
However, now, if I hear an honorific in Japanese... but then they translate it to the English equivalent or just don't use it at all in a sub, I feel a weird inconsistency. "Why aren't they doing the translation as close to literal as possible?" I often think. <br />
<br />
So instead of complaining both ways, I'll suggest a solution: An option to turn on/turn off translation notes, just like captions in YouTube videos, or something. But then again, it would make it harder for the subbers, so output would slow down... AHH! This is a hard one. I'd just keep it the way it is, some honorifics included, some translated or omitted, so that both new people and people who have been watching anime can feel satisfied.</div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig"><!--link--><a href="http://myanimelist.net/animelist/einonymous&amp;sclick=1"><img class="userimg" data-src="http://myanimelist.net/signature/einonymous.png" /></a> </div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
