		  </td>
		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message31343823">Someone asked me about this question recently to me because I know the Japanese ergo I am apparently the smartest person in the field. Since Chinese has honorifics too, I guess I have more say than the common nerd. So this is more or less an extension of that answer.<br />
<br />
Anyway, whenever I work for a translation or scanlation (why would you), I usually look over the script and see if honorifics are preferred or not by the team. I'm usually the junior translator and translation checker, so I don't have any say. Not that I care because I'm not a stickler for NO HONORIFICS or YES HONORIFICS. It isn't a matter of life and death, yo.<br />
<br />
But if I have the chance, I would probably take them out. -san is the most pointless honorific if kept in a non-Japanese language; it denotes very little in English at least. I also find that people will get confused if Japanese characters start adding -san into companies, which has nothing to do with Mitt Romney's platform I assure you -- it's just a sign of respect. Also, bookstore owner-san is kinda silly.<br />
<br />
So regarding information loss when it comes to honorifics, I wouldn't cry much about it. A lot of characters in high school settings just use first names (TL Note: calling out first names is either a sign of intimacy or being rude), so you rarely see it in other works. A goshujinsama doesn't sound as cool as Master in English.  Unless you like romaji, which is EW.<br />
<br />
However, there are times that you would want to keep it. I think the charm of Zaregoto's detective-chan is lost because she likes to add a multitude of honorifics to her title because she's that badass. And as everyone mentioned, honorifics should be kept if it makes sense in the story and setting. Like that senpai thing Kuiper mentioned. Kouhai-senpai relations are cute.<br />
<br />
But I still feel that honorifics in subtitles look silly. And it's hard to say that even if the senpai in FMF you will understand the complex kouhai-senpai Confucian thingmajig relationships. But it's not a big deal anyway once you can understand it.<br />
<br />
Just as an example: For those who want to see how an official localization uses honorifics and fucks it up, read the Strawberry Panic omnibus light novel. I can assure you that you will send death threats to me or at least ask for a $10 refund because it's one of the strangest piece of work you'll ever read. For those who don't know Strawberry Panic, it's basically a clone of Marimite. Except it's gayer and makes lesbianing a competition. Everyone in the localization goes -sama and -senpai erryday my brain starts bleeding.<br />
<br />
In Japanese literature, it is common to not see honorifics. I guess the Murakami translators didn't give a shit and putting -san sounds just too silly. I don't see much of it in Soseki and Dazai too -- with one exception: Kokoro has a giant TL note about how sensei is a really deep word that denotes many deep things. <br />
<br />
So when I see them pros do both ways, I find that I lean towards the no-honorifics allowed route because it looks nicer to read. I guess subtitles are different from prose for most people, but my opinion stays the same.<br />
<br />
Anyway, I suggest a solution as good as einonymous -- but it will solve all problems: learn Japanese. No need to quarrel about FANSUBS and SCANLATIONS. Aw yis, smoke nil 420 anime erryday.</div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig">I work in <!--link--><a href="http://vntls.tindabox.net/staff/kastel" rel="nofollow">VNs</a>. Sometimes, they have h-scenes and I go "waai~". I also like to not write at <!--link--><a href="http://oppaiisjustice.wordpress.com/" rel="nofollow">Oppai is Justice</a>, a blog with great urls.</div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
